# DashDiag (.cursorrules)
# Go 1.22+ · Static binary · Read-only diagnostic CLI
# module: github.com/keyorixhq/dashdiag
# "One command → instant system health overview"
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## PRODUCT IDENTITY (never deviate from these)

This is DashDiag — a Go CLI tool that takes a read-only snapshot of system
health and exits. It NEVER modifies the system, NEVER runs as a daemon,
NEVER makes network calls from collectors (only from platform/ and init/).

The tool must work as a single static binary with zero runtime dependencies.
Every feature must satisfy all six design constraints:
1. Works offline
2. No external API calls by default
3. Completes in < 35 seconds
4. Read-only — no side effects on the checked system
5. Zero-config for basic use
6. Single static binary — no venv, no node_modules, no runtime deps

Module path: github.com/keyorixhq/dashdiag


## ARCHITECTURE — LAYERED PIPELINE (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

The dependency direction is ONE-WAY and NEVER reversed:

  cmd → runner → collectors → models ← analysis ← render ← output

Permitted imports:
  cmd/          imports: runner, analysis, render, output, platform, baseline, tips, tui, version, config
  runner/       imports: collectors, models ONLY
  collectors/   imports: models, platform ONLY
  models/       imports: NOTHING internal (stdlib only)
  analysis/     imports: models, config, platform ONLY
  render/       imports: models, output, baseline ONLY
  output/       imports: NOTHING internal (stdlib + lipgloss only)
  platform/     imports: NOTHING internal (stdlib only)
  baseline/     imports: models, runner, output
  tips/         imports: output, version ONLY
  tui/          imports: output ONLY
  init/         imports: platform, output ONLY
  config/       imports: NOTHING internal (stdlib + viper only)

FORBIDDEN import directions (cause circular dependencies):
  collectors importing analysis   — NEVER
  collectors importing render     — NEVER
  models importing anything internal — NEVER
  output importing models         — NEVER
  analysis importing render       — NEVER


## LAYER CONTRACTS (each layer has ONE job)

### Collectors
- Pure functions: input = context.Context, output = (interface{}, error)
- Return RAW data only — never set Status, StatusReason, or thresholds
- Never spawn goroutines — the runner owns all concurrency
- Implement the Collector interface:
    Name()    string
    Timeout() time.Duration
    Collect(ctx context.Context) (interface{}, error)
- Read /proc, /sys files directly — never shell out for basic metrics
- Shell out ONLY when no file API exists (exec.CommandContext always, never exec.Command)
- Always provide macOS fallback (check runtime.GOOS == "darwin")

### Models
- Dumb structs ONLY — no methods, no logic, no validation
- Every exported field has a json struct tag
- Status fields: string type, values "OK"|"WARN"|"CRIT"|"INFO"|"PENDING"
- StatusReason field: human-readable explanation string

### Analysis
- THE ONLY PLACE that sets Status and StatusReason
- Reads raw collector output, applies thresholds, produces []models.Insight
- Thresholds come from config (user-configurable), with hardcoded defaults

### Runner
- Owns ALL concurrency — runs collectors in parallel with goroutines
- Each collector gets its own ctx derived from parent with collector.Timeout()
- Results stream through a channel — never buffer all results in memory
- Never panics on collector error — wraps in Result{Err: err}

### cmd/ files (commands)
- WIRING ONLY — connect flags to packages
- Maximum 80 lines per file
- No business logic — if you write an if-statement not about flags, move it


## DASHDIAG-SPECIFIC PATTERNS — CURSOR COMMONLY GETS THESE WRONG

### 1. Cgroup-aware resource collection (CRITICAL)
DashDiag runs INSIDE containers. /proc/meminfo returns HOST RAM, not container
limit. Always use ContainerContext to get effective limits.

### 2. IO collectors require TWO samples
/proc/diskstats has cumulative counters. Read TWICE with 1s gap, compute delta.
Single read = meaningless absolute numbers.

### 3. Parsers must accept io.Reader not hardcoded /proc paths
WRONG: os.ReadFile("/proc/vmstat") inside Collect()
RIGHT: parseVMStat(r io.Reader) — inject file in tests, open in production

### 4. Platform files need build tags
//go:build linux  on linux.go
//go:build darwin on macos.go

### 5. state.json writes must be atomic
Use temp file + os.Rename() — never direct os.WriteFile on state.json

### 6. Cobra subcommand pattern for deep variants
healthCmd.AddCommand(healthDeepCmd) — NOT rootCmd.AddCommand(healthDeepCmd)
Results in: dsd health deep (correct), NOT dsd health-deep (wrong)

### 7. Exit codes must flow from insights, not error handling
0=all OK, 1=WARN, 2=CRIT. Derive from highest severity insight.
os.Exit() permitted ONLY in cmd/ files for this purpose.

### 8. Context must be propagated, never re-created
WRONG: context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), ...) inside a collector
RIGHT: use the ctx passed to Collect(ctx context.Context)

### 9. Lipgloss colours must be adaptive
WRONG: lipgloss.Color("#FF0000")
RIGHT: lipgloss.AdaptiveColor{Light: "#CC0000", Dark: "#FF6B6B"}
Define ALL styles in internal/render/styles.go — nowhere else.

### 10. Cloud environment affects IO thresholds
AWS EBS await WARN=5ms CRIT=20ms (not bare-metal 1ms/5ms)
Always check platform.CloudEnvironment in analysis layer.


## GO CODE QUALITY RULES

- NEVER ignore errors with bare _  (exception: defer f.Close())
- Always wrap errors: fmt.Errorf("reading /proc/loadavg: %w", err)
- Every function that does I/O takes context.Context as first arg
- Always exec.CommandContext(ctx,...) — never exec.Command(...)
- Always http.NewRequestWithContext(ctx,...) — never http.Get(...)
- Maximum function length: 50 lines
- Maximum nesting depth: 3 levels
- Pre-allocate slices: make([]T, 0, n)
- Use bufio.Scanner for line-by-line file reading


## SECURITY RULES

- NEVER use user input directly in file paths — filepath.Clean() first
- NEVER use exec.Command without context
- NEVER shell out with string interpolation: exec.Command("sh", "-c", "ls "+input)
- Only write to ~/.dsd/ — never to system directories
- No credentials in code or config files


## TESTING RULES

- Every collector: parser unit tests + golden file test + fuzz test
- Every model: JSON round-trip test
- Every renderer: golden file test
- Every threshold: table-driven boundary test (below/at/above WARN and CRIT)
- t.Parallel() at top of every test and sub-test
- NEVER read real /proc in tests — use testdata/fixtures/
- Use t.TempDir() for any test that writes files
- Golden files in testdata/golden/, update with: go test ./... -update


## OUTPUT FORMAT RULES

- ALL progress output to STDERR — stdout stays clean for --json
- Never fmt.Printf with raw ANSI codes — always lipgloss
- --json must always be valid JSON (validate in tests)
- --plain must work in CI (no ANSI, no emoji)
- Exit codes: 0=OK, 1=WARN, 2=CRIT (public contract, never change)


## CONFIDENCE THRESHOLD — WHEN TO ASK VS WHEN TO ACT

STOP and ask ONE question when:
- Scope is ambiguous (which file? which collector?)
- Architecture decision required (which layer owns this?)
- About to overwrite existing file with content
- About to change JSON output schema (public contract)
- About to change exit code behaviour
- Prompt references something not visible in codebase

ACT immediately without asking:
- Formatting, import ordering, gofmt
- Adding error wrapping context strings
- Writing tests for code just generated
- Filling in obvious boilerplate following existing patterns
- Fixing a compilation error with obvious solution

Ask format: ❓ Before I proceed: [single specific question]
             My assumption if you say "go ahead": [what I'll do]


## TOKEN EFFICIENCY — RESPONSE FORMAT RULES

- Start responses with code or the clarifying question — no prose preamble
- Never "Sure! I'd be happy to..." or "Great question!"
- Show only what changes when modifying existing files — not full file rewrites
- One short paragraph max after code (explain non-obvious decisions only)
- Do not repeat the user's question back
- Do not add "Let me know if you need changes!" at the end
- Do not write TODO comments — either implement or leave it out


## WHEN ASKED TO BUILD SOMETHING

Before writing any code:
1. Which layer? (collector? analysis? render? cmd?)
2. Does the import direction work?
3. Does a model already exist for this data?
4. Does a similar collector/renderer exist to follow the pattern?

When in doubt: make it simpler. Ship the minimal correct implementation first.

